ACTIVIST SPOTLIGHT @j3nnyali üì£ ‚ÄúHello! I am Jannat Ali, a trans woman activist from Pakistan. Last year, in December, we made history and organized Pakistan‚Äôs FIRST EVER Pride March in Lahore. It was exciting, empowering and emotional. We felt that we had achieved so much, like never before. I‚Äôm trying to do the same this year, but I need your help! Many of the participants will be arriving from remote areas, so money for transport is crucial. More importantly, security is essential ‚Äì transphobia and homophobia are rife everywhere, but especially in Pakistan. 
Calling on all my sisters, brothers, friends and allies from all colours of the rainbow to help me with this campaign. Donate what you can so that the LGBTQ community in Pakistan are heard. So that we can hold our heads high and march with pride!

P.S Pride is normally celebrated in the summer but for us in Lahore, it's too hot. So December is ideal. Also for security reasons we have not disclosed the precise date. Hope you can understand! :)‚Äù #activist #activistspotlight #socialchange #lahore #lgbtq ‚Äî To Donate Swipe up in I Weigh stories.

RG @alokvmenon - ‚ÄúDespite what mainstream media will show you ‚Äî  white people are not the first to challenge gender stereotypes + or be non-binary. Black + brown people have been leading the fight against gender norms for hundreds of years. As awareness of gender fluidity + non-binary expression make it to the mainstream it is often through white bodies because this ~apparently~ makes it easier for society to digest. Sometimes it‚Äôs about implicit bias ‚Äî we are more likely to see whiteness as innovative, as leadership, as the prototype. In this landscape it is worth repeating: the origin of transphobia in the Western world is racism and the violence of the gender binary will only be adequately addressed by addressing racism. It‚Äôs not enough to critique media whitewashing, we must actively celebrate + uplift BiPOC gender variant people who have been fighting for ages but are constantly misrecognized + disappeared. Here are 11 Black gender variant creatives across the world who have deeply moved me this past year. FAKA @desiremarea @felagucci musicians, style icons (South Africa), @olavetalks scholar activist (Belgium, Netherlands, Burundi), @surprisinghealthbenefits fashion designer, artist (USA), @marikiscrycrycry dancer/choreographer (UK), @steroidbeyonce model, writer (USA), @miles_jai beauty guru, performer (USA), @chezzie_b dancer/choreographer (South Africa), @kamalamackerel interdisciplinary artist (Canada, Mauritius), @asos_ari model, content creator (USA), @aicy_ray illustrator, activist (Portugal, Guinea-Bissau). Follow them + immerse yourself in their creative genius. #degenderfashion ‚Äú #iweigh #activists #activism.

Boundaries for the holiday season üéÑ 
By trauma therapist @kelseymech ‚ÄúThis is a hard time of year when it comes to setting boundaries. There can be so much pressure to spend time with people we don‚Äôt really want to see, to fulfill obligations and expectations that really don‚Äôt feel good for us, or simply to take on too much when all we want is to rest and relax. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Boundaries are your friend - all the time, even when they are hard, but especially at this time of year. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Here are some of my favourite suggestions when it comes to setting boundaries and some examples for how you can put these into action. ‚Å£
‚Å£
- Put up a wall, but also open a door. If you are saying no to one thing, can you offer something else instead? ‚Å£
- That being said, it is also okay to JUST SAY NO. And you don‚Äôt need a reason or justification. ‚Å£
- Being clear and honest is kind and helpful for the other person. It‚Äôs better than beating around the bush, or saying yes and then having to bail later. ‚Å£
- If you struggle with setting boundaries, gratitude can go a long way. You can always include a ‚Äúthank you for understanding‚Äù or appreciation for an offer, even if you are turning something down. ‚Å£
- Ultimately, focus on how you want to feel and use that as your motivation to set boundaries even when it is hard and uncomfortable. Your needs and desires are just as important as everyone else‚Äôs. And, they should be *the most* important to you. ‚Å£
‚Å£
I‚Äôd love to hear - what boundaries do you need to set this year? What gets in your way of setting boundaries? Tell me everything!‚Äù #iweigh #boundaries.

Activist Spotlight üì£
@nogalevyrapoport Noga Levy-Rapoport (she/her) is an 18-year-old climate justice activist, organising the youth climate strikes with the UK Student Climate Network (@ukscn) since February this year, focusing on dismantling the roots of the climate crisis: colonialism, imperialism, and neoliberalism. Her organising centres around the systemic nature of the climate and ecological emergency, fighting for an internationalist Green New Deal that will bring justice to the Global South through a globalist just transition for the vulnerable and marginalised, preventing ecological collapse and protecting the defenceless from climate disasters that are already inevitable. She believes the best and most important change you can make is to strike, to take direct action, to organise and empower at home, at school, at work, to get out onto the streets and fight to tear down the unjust and unfair framework of our society, to overhaul our failed system and fight for climate justice. Noga also co-directs a youth theatre company, @tea.theatre, to support young people in her community to explore drama and theatre without fear of judgement or financial burden. Currently studying her A-Levels, the activist and advocate hopes to go on to be an opera singer if we manage to save the world. #iweigh #activist #climateactivist

üëèüèæ@emilyonlife - ‚ÄúCapitalism and patriarchy and white supremacy and heteronormativity are the co-owners of the Modern Western Culture Factory, which operates 24 hours a day, continuously devising new and insidious ways to condition us to the belief that we are not enough. There are trillions of dollars being made on our fruitless and endless attempts to shop and diet and straighten and please our way into an impossible future version of ourselves that we feel deserves our love and acceptance. And if we‚Äôre distracted with self-hatred, doubt, and fear, we‚Äôre diluting our own power and motivation to change and challenge their systems. ‚ñ™Ô∏è
So yeah‚Äî if loving yourself feels weird and uncomfortable, OF COURSE IT DOES. You‚Äôre fighting decades of cultural messaging‚Äî not to mention what messages you may have internalized from your family and friends and people in your seventh grade math class (who are all also reacting to the same cultural messaging). It feeling uncomfortable and hard doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre bad at it. It doesn‚Äôt mean you can‚Äôt do it. And it sure as shit doesn‚Äôt mean you don‚Äôt deserve it. Keep going, one thought at a time, one small act at a time. Undoing all that conditioning takes time and repetition. You‚Äôre doing great.‚Äù #emilyonlife #loveyourself #iweigh #loveyourselfquotes #howtoloveyourself #selfhealers #youareenough

IT‚ÄôS THE MOST WASTEFUL TIME OF THE YEAR‚Ä¶ üåé‚ôªüå≤‚Ä®But climate activists @VenetiaFalconer + @MaxLaManna are here to explain how small, conscious decisions can help make this time of year wonderful!‚Å£ üçΩPrioritise filling your plates with more plants as these are the foods that tend to have the lowest carbon footprint.‚Å£
ü•¶We waste one third of the food we create globally, so make sure you eat your leftovers, or give them to those in need.‚Å£
üéÅWhen it comes to gifts, experiences are the way to go! Staycations, concert tickets, spa treatments‚Ä¶ or plan the perfect day for your loved one.‚Ä®üéÄIn the UK alone, we waste enough wrapping paper every year to circle the globe 9 TIMES. So when wrapping your gifts: prioritise what you already have: old newspapers, magazines, and scarves. Avoid plastic sellotape where you can and up-cycle any cards, tags and ribbons.‚Å£
ü¶åDon‚Äôt feel like you ‚Äòneed‚Äô a new outfit for the party season. Try swapping, renting or thrifting instead‚Ä®üéÑMillions of Christmas trees will end up as landfill and this causes harmful greenhouse gases. If you have an artificial one: keep using it. If you‚Äôre hankering for a real one, try replanting or renting it. And make sure you compost/recycle it properly - check with your local authorities‚Å£
‚ùÑUse the holiday season as an excuse to spend more time offline. This a great way to look agfter out mental health and encourage those around us to make planet friendly steps. Give @48HourChallenge a go if you can.‚Å£
